article.headline: N.J.I.T. 56, Manhattan 55
article.story: NEW YORK (AP) -- Clayton Barker's underhanded reverse layup with 31 seconds left helped New Jersey Institute of Technology overcome a 14-point second-half deficit to defeat Manhattan 56-55 in its first game as a Division I team. Barker and Nesho Milosevic each scored 12 points and Kraig Peters added 11 to lead the Highlanders. Arturo Dubois scored 13 points and Christian Jackson 11 for the Jaspers in the head coaching debut for former Pitt associate Barry Rohrssen. Manhattan had a chance at the buzzer, but a 3-point try by Jackson bounded off the rim. The Jaspers, ahead 33-25 at halftime, scored the first six points of the second half to take a 39-25 lead with 16:11 remaining. Milosevic's basket capped a 14-0 scoring run that netted the Highlanders a 41-40 edge with 11:12 to go. Barker scored with 1:44 left to give NJIT a 54-53 lead but a defensive rebound tip by Milosevic off a shot by Dubois went in and actually put Manhattan on top 55-54 with 44 seconds left. It was the season opener for both teams.
